The Democratic summit ends, Biden says the fire of freedom will never go out
The virtual "Summit for Democracy", convened by U.S. President Joe Biden and attended by governments from 110 countries around the world as well as civil society and private sector leaders, concluded Friday (Dec. 10).
In his closing remarks, Biden said that the fire of freedom is burning in the hearts of everyone in the world, and an authoritarian regime will never be able to put it out.
He also said that he plans to hold the second global "democracy summit" next year.
The Taiwan government representative and political councillor Tang Feng, and Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Luo Guancong, who is in exile in the UK, also spoke at the summit on the second day.
"We know how difficult the job ahead of us is," Biden said.
But we also know that we can rise to the challenge because, as I have said before, as this summit has shown, democracy is everywhere.
A tyrannical regime can never extinguish the little fire of liberty that burns in the hearts of people all over the world and around the world.”
Biden also said that defending democracy requires the joint efforts of the entire society.
"As leaders of government, we have a responsibility to listen to our citizens, strengthen the guardrails of democracy, and push for reforms that enable transparent and accountable governance, more resistant to the buffers and shocks of authoritarianism, and those who want to run naked in pursuit of power before the public good," he said.
The themes of the second day of the "Democracy Summit" are defending human rights, consolidating democracy and confronting authoritarianism, and countering digital authoritarianism and affirming democratic values.
This day coincides with International Human Rights Day.
UN Secretary-General António Guterres also said in his opening speech that the cause of democracy faces challenges around the world, especially those brought about by emerging digital technologies.
"It is time to reaffirm shared values and positions and democratic resilience," he said.
This requires deepening social dialogue, tackling inequality, fighting corruption, renewing the social contract, investing in quality education, and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
It also requires a firm condemnation of populism, nativism and extremism in all its forms, including using all the tools the technological revolution has to offer.”
Speaking to the summit via a pre-recorded video, Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Luo Guancong reminded attendees of their ongoing concern over the human rights situation in Hong Kong and China's ethnic minorities such as the Uighurs and Tibetans.
"For too long, the world has embraced the rise of China without a mechanism to hold it accountable," he said.
That is why politicians and civil society leaders must cooperate.
We have to use everything (resources) we have to ensure that the revival of democracy is our first priority.”
Luo Guancong also called on the free world to unite against the threat of the CCP.
He said: "Maybe some of you are afraid to annoy General Secretary Xi Jinping, maybe some of you don't want to lose the Chinese market, maybe some of you don't recognize the threat to our democratic values.
And that's why we failed.
That's why we have to change.”
During a roundtable discussion on "Combating Digital Primitive Democratism and affirming democratic values", Tang Feng, a political committee member of Taiwan's Executive Yuan, released a "State Statement" via video, emphasizing that Taiwan stands at the forefront of fighting dictatorship and authoritarianism.
He also shared his experience on how to fight the new crown epidemic through information transparency and building mutual trust.
"As democracy in Taiwan is in the ascendant, we always stand firmly at the forefront of the global fight against authoritarianism, and take a leadership role in promoting global freedom, democracy and human rights," he said.
During the pandemic, global democracy is showing signs of going backwards as authoritarian governments everywhere rationalize human rights violations in the name of public health and collective good.
In Taiwan, however, we can control the epidemic without closing the city, and defeat disinformation without taking it off the shelves.”
During the second day of the "Democracy Summit", the U.S. Treasury Department announced the imposition of sanctions on 15 individuals and 10 entities from several countries, including China and North Korea, who were藜estly violated human rights. It also imposed investment restrictions on a Chinese company that was found to have used surveillance technology to assist in human rights violations.
