Xinhua News Agency, Washington, May 23 (Reporter Xu Jianmei) More than 130 Asian American groups in the United States filed complaints with the U.S. Department of Education and the Department of Justice on the 23rd, protesting the three Ivy League schools — Yale University, Brown University and Dartmouth College discriminate against Asian applicants in the admissions process.
The Asian American Education Alliance, which led the complaint, held a press conference in Washington that day.
Zhao Yukong, chairman of the group, said at the press conference that in the past 10 years, the number of Asian applicants who meet admission requirements for top American schools has doubled. But in these three prestigious American schools, the proportion of Asian Americans has remained at the same level.
Numerous studies have shown that these colleges and universities "persistently and systematically discriminate against Asian applicants" in their so-called "general-based" admissions process.
Zhao Yukong introduced that in 2014, a study by Sanders and other scholars showed that in the three colleges and universities, Asian Americans have the lowest admission rate of all ethnic groups relative to the number of applicants.
Data from the U.S. Department of Education also shows that Brown University and Dartmouth College have the lowest percentages of Asian-American applicants among all Ivy League schools, and Yale University and Brown University have implemented de facto racial quotas for Asian-American applicants for more than 20 years.
Zhao Yukong told Xinhua that they expected that after filing the complaint, the U.S. Department of Education and Justice would investigate and take measures to prevent these universities from continuing to discriminate against Asians in their admissions after finding the facts.
They also hope that the complainants' universities will take the initiative to take this issue seriously and change their admissions policies for Asian Americans.
At present, the three universities that have been complained have not responded.
The Asian American Education Coalition was founded in 2015 when it filed a complaint against Harvard University for admissions discrimination, but the U.S. Department of Education rejected it on procedural grounds.
In addition to Chinese American groups, the parties involved in the complaint include American Indian, Korean, Japanese, and Pakistani educational groups.
